Tabs

The tabs are used on the PDP, Recipes page and the offers page.

JavaScript is used to show/hide the tabs when they are selected.

The more information tab appears on a PDP if the product has an attachment sent with the product information and is set up in management centre.

At the moment there are no products like this on the live site but the code for this scenario exists.

The class of .first is used on the first list item to remove the left margin from the tab.

The class of .currentTab is used to indicate the selected tab.

The orange "buy ingredients" tab appears on the recipes pages. The class of .important is used for the tab to be orange.

When the "buy ingredients" tab is the selected tab it looks the same as all the other tabs when they are selected.

The offers page looks similar to the PDP page.

The content of all the tabs can be very different on each of the tabs and the different pages. The styling of the tabs content is out of scope for this style guide.

Tooltips

JavaScript is used to position the tooltips either to the top, bottom, right or left of the tooltip icon.

CSS classes .JSTooltipPositionedTop, .JSTooltipPositionedBottom, .JSTooltipPositionedRight and .JSTooltipPositionedLeft determine the positioning of the content and the tooltip arrow.

NB The position of the tooltip is in relation to the tooltip link icon and not the arrow itself.

For example, .JSTooltipPositionedTop has the arrow at the bottom of the tooltip content.

Filters

When JavaScript is enabled the apply filter button is hidden and the form auto submits when a checkbox option is toggled.

The whole filter can be opened and closed and the dietary options can be opened and closed as well. Arrow icons appear to indicate that the sections can be toggled.

When a filter is applied, options that can no longer be selected are disabled and appear in a light grey colour.

Form Sections

Form sections are used to style all the forms in the main content area on the site.

They all have a form section heading and body.

The form body can have all the types of form content e.g. radio buttons, checkboxes, input fields etc.

The key pages using the form sections are the registration page, the billing address page and the checkout pages.

Sometimes form sections have a form footer as well. For example for call to action links and submit buttons.

NB on the payments page the form section is also used as a wrapper for the trolley summary content and the styles are dependent on the body id of "billingDetails".

Form Fields

All the form fields are in a div with a class of "field".

The labels for inputs and select fields are in a div with a class of "indicator".

The input and select fields are in a div with a class of "input".

The radio buttons are in a div with a class of "radios".

The checkboxes are in a div with a class of "checkboxes".

If a validation error occurs, an additional class of "error" appears in the div with a class of "field".

An error message also appears above the input in a div called "errorText".

When one field or the next field needs to be filled in, the error message appears between the two of them.

The input with an error has a red border and a red arrow appears next to it.

When a button needs to appear next to an input field, a div with a class of "inputFieldContainer" is used for the input and a div with a class of "buttonContainer" is used for the button.

When an error occurs an error summary also appears at the top of the page with jump links to each of the fields with an error.

Zone

Zone and department pages can have espots next to the lists of links.

A "flexContainer" class is added to the "section" div and additional "flexFixedContent" and "flexLiquidContent" wrap around the links and espots respectively.

The departments, aisles and shelves are in individual unordered lists with accessible h2 subheadings.

A zone page has a list of links of departments and a two column width espot.

Department

Department pages have lists of department links and aisle links and a one column width espot.

The selected department has a class of "current" and has an orange background that matches the breadcrumb level.

There are hidden jump links to the aisle links.

Special offers have a class of "offers" on the list item that holds the special offfers link. This makes the link text bold and orange.

Aisle

Aisle pages do not have any espots so they do not have any additional classes or divs added to them.

Aisle pages have lists of department links, aisle links and shelf links.

They have hidden jump links to the aisle and shelf links.

Please note the shelf pages are the product lister pages. Only the breadcrumb appears on those pages.

Table Container

Please note that the "tableContainer" class is also used for the mini trolley on the right hand side. Please be very careful when changing any styles and check the mini trolley still looks as expected.

The "tableContainer" is used on several different pages and it is important to check all the variations when making amends to it. A quick search for the class in the jsp files will come up with around 15 different instances of it.

The border, border radius, margin and positioning are the key styles that are used across the different pages.

The "tableContainer" class is also used in selectors to style headings, tables, buttons and general layout tweaks like padding and margin on some elements.

Classes in wrapper divs to override the styles of the table container are used on some pages. Please double check other pages that are using this component when making changes to it.

The OrderItemDisplay.jsp is very similar to the my trolley page but without the CSS classes on the table.

OrderSummary.jsp is very similar to the full trolley page.

LogoutScheduledOrderSlot.jsp is very similar to LogoutScheduledOrderNoSlot.jsp but it has an h3 instead of an h2

Please note that there may be some amend order and auto order pages that are not covered here. However they are likely to be very similar to these examples.

Great Offers Espots

The great offers components are displayed next to each other in rows on the site.

They are displayed beneath each other here because they are rendered with different data snippets.

Modern browsers that can handle flexbox ensure that the heights of the boxes in each row is the same.

The heights of the boxes on different rows can be different.

The space for the offer title is 2 lines. Boxes will grow to fit the product titles.

The pricing and add to basket button will not necessarily line up in the rows.

The "favouritesOffersList" class is needed on the wrapping div for the favourites products to be displayed with a blue border and a blue product name.

Enhanced Security

We use Verified by Visa and MasterCard SecureCode to ensure that only you can use your card to prevent card fraud.

What are they?

Verified by Visa and MasterCard SecureCode work in a similar way as Chip and Pin, protecting your cards with a password which only you will know for use when shopping online.

How do they work?

You only need to register each card once. Once you have done that you can use your password whenever you use that card to shop online as extra validation to give you peace of mind.

How do I register?

Simply follow the instructions. The password you create is linked to your card, rather like Chip and Pin. Once you have registered your bank will hold your password securely, Sainsbury's won't have access to it, and you will be able to use this password with other participating retailers when paying with the same card.

What if I have already registered?

If you have already registered your card with us or someone else you will be asked to enter your password. Please follow the instructions and if you have any problems please contact your bank/card issuer for help.
